Sure! I have created a basic program in Java that will print the first 10 numbers of the Fibonacci sequence. The Fibonacci sequence is a series of numbers where each number is the sum of the two preceding numbers. The sequence starts with 0 and 1, and each subsequent number is the sum of the two numbers that came before it.

public class Fibonacci {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int first = 0, second = 1, third = 1;
        System.out.println(first);
        System.out.println(second);
        while (third <= 10) {
            third = first + second;
            first = second;
            second = third;
            System.out.println(third);
        }
    }
}

This program starts by defining three variables first, second, and third. The first two numbers in the Fibonacci sequence are always 0 and 1, so the first two numbers are assigned to first and second. The third number is calculated by adding the first and second numbers. The program then enters a while loop that will continue until the third number is greater than or equal to 10. In each iteration of the loop, the third number is assigned to first, first is assigned to second, and the third number is added to second to get the next number in the sequence. The third number is then printed.

